WEBVTT

00:08.400 --> 00:12.340
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

00:27.940 --> 00:33.240
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

00:35.880 --> 00:37.540
And here are your hosts.

00:41.460 --> 00:43.580
This is Bill Vernon and Darrell Lane.

00:43.740 --> 00:46.580
Janet Morris has written seven science fiction novels so far.

00:47.000 --> 00:51.260
These are grouped into two series, the Solistria series and the Saga of the Carian Empire.

00:51.760 --> 00:55.580
Morris's novels are characterized by strongly developed characters and well-drawn backgrounds,

00:55.780 --> 00:56.800
and they feature hard science.

00:57.300 --> 01:01.860
The Solistria series consists of four novels, High Couch of Solistria, The Golden Sword,

01:02.320 --> 01:04.660
Wind from the Abyss, and The Carnelian Throne.

01:04.660 --> 01:08.960
The protagonist of the series is Estri, the courtesan who gradually learns more about her

01:08.960 --> 01:10.660
real identity and the power she is inherited.

01:11.340 --> 01:14.000
The series, still incomplete, chronicles Estri's awakening.

01:14.340 --> 01:16.920
We asked Morris what she was aiming at when she wrote the series.

01:17.860 --> 01:23.360
I was asked to return to come to terms with the fact that logically and mathematically,

01:23.720 --> 01:29.520
I couldn't come to terms with the incidents of the ESP that I experienced in my own life,

01:29.520 --> 01:37.640
and some of the more tenuous philosophical intuitions that I was having that I just couldn't state.

01:38.140 --> 01:41.840
There's no other way really to state those concepts on one level.

01:42.980 --> 01:52.080
The relationship of mind to probability, our connection to time, whether we indeed are co-creators

01:52.080 --> 01:56.860
in some sense of the universe in which we're living and we're making a future in the past at

01:56.860 --> 02:02.280
once, and sometimes in particle physics I begin to wonder if the universe isn't just giving us

02:02.280 --> 02:06.820
whatever particle we choose to dream up, you know, as soon as we think it up then it comes into being

02:07.620 --> 02:11.880
because we seem to be going further and further down and every time we go down another level,

02:12.000 --> 02:14.940
I mean the quark split up into little quarks and it's endless.

02:16.480 --> 02:20.320
And a lot of times you could come up with a good mathematical reason for something,

02:20.420 --> 02:26.700
then maybe the universe is convinced and it produces, I have no idea of whether that's going to

02:26.700 --> 02:33.000
turn out to be what it is, but if indeed it is, if the anthropic principle is anywhere near valid,

02:33.200 --> 02:38.200
that it is something like that happening, that we are in a sense central to creation,

02:38.500 --> 02:40.420
which would be nice. I mean it suits my ink, it just...

02:45.840 --> 02:47.720
Morris had other aims in mind as well.

02:48.180 --> 02:54.180
On another level I wanted to talk about genetic predispositions and very bright people

02:55.660 --> 03:01.900
have a particular problem with both human relationships and sexuality and I wanted to

03:01.900 --> 03:07.580
talk about that because no matter how intelligent and logical you are at a certain point you have

03:07.580 --> 03:12.400
to deal with what is your genetic conditioning and you really get a snoop full of it in a sex act,

03:13.420 --> 03:20.120
a person who is intelligent and monitors what's happening to them as they become around,

03:20.120 --> 03:27.200
really realizes that there is a different and much more primeval person inside each of us and

03:28.460 --> 03:36.260
I had at that time begun to despair of nurture having anything to do at all with human behavior,

03:36.460 --> 03:42.020
thinking that it was almost everything we do seem to me at that point, time to be genetically prompted.

03:43.000 --> 03:51.240
What Ed Wilson said that the urge to creativity might be inextricably linked to the desire

03:51.240 --> 03:54.720
to own and dominate and that's one of the central themes there.

03:55.360 --> 03:57.920
Morris' upbringing also influenced her writing the series.

03:58.820 --> 04:04.360
I was sort of born post-deliberated, I was the guy, I was the oldest child and I was very intelligent

04:04.360 --> 04:10.580
and I was expected to do all the things that any young man was supposed to do so I had come to

04:10.580 --> 04:16.680
grips with being a post-deliberated female and these people were trying to get to where I started

04:16.680 --> 04:22.560
out in agony, these women's livers not realizing what they were letting themselves in for, I also

04:22.560 --> 04:29.300
wanted to talk about that and the Estri persona is a persona that is in no way

04:31.840 --> 04:37.900
less than holy female while being very intelligent and reasonably comfortable with that talent.

04:38.620 --> 04:43.280
So I wanted to talk about it, it was an injection at that time that was putting into consciousness

04:43.280 --> 04:48.240
to sort of inoculate people against extremes of the female liberation.

04:49.260 --> 04:51.920
More on Janet and Morris' Solistor series on our next show.

