06:12.700 --> 06:17.820
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on Science Fiction and Fantasy

06:20.620 --> 06:22.160
and here are your hosts.

06:26.180 --> 06:28.100
This is Daryl Lane and Bill Vernon.

06:28.540 --> 06:32.320
Janet and Morris' four-volume Solistor series has had a highly successful sales record.

06:32.320 --> 06:36.420
With this series, it's interesting to know that although the books themselves are explicitly

06:36.420 --> 06:41.220
Science Fiction, they're packaged as fantasy. Right, the covers in all four of the novels feature

06:41.220 --> 06:45.840
a scantily clad voluptuous woman holding a sword, a scene typical of countless fantasy novels.

06:46.040 --> 06:50.200
And the spines of two of the novels actually say fantasy under the publisher's colifen.

06:50.680 --> 06:52.880
We asked Morris why the novels appeared with these covers.

06:53.880 --> 06:58.480
The difference in that particular case was that Fred Rick Paul, who was my first editor,

06:58.480 --> 07:05.960
who knew what was Science Fiction left, and the other, I guess, operative difference was that

07:05.960 --> 07:09.100
at the point in time when they came out, they could get a big old print run if they called it

07:09.100 --> 07:15.360
fantasy. So it was an editorial difference rather than a real difference, but those covers did not

07:15.360 --> 07:20.780
help me in the least get those books to the kind of people that I should be reading them.

07:28.680 --> 07:32.420
Here Morris goes on to tell us her feelings about Science Fiction and fantasy.

07:58.560 --> 08:03.600
Problems and questions is just as important as showing that you indeed do understand

08:04.280 --> 08:08.820
this or that particular principle, which seems right now to be valid until next week. It turns

08:08.820 --> 08:14.720
out that, well, it just was fudge factor. So I don't know if there's a difference for me,

08:15.600 --> 08:21.700
unfortunately. Fantasy right now seems to be where the writers go that don't do any homework

08:22.420 --> 08:29.240
and don't really understand either this world or the principles on which fantasy was originally

08:29.240 --> 08:35.000
based, the Homeric tradition and a good sense of history and honor and all those nice things that

08:35.000 --> 08:42.540
we don't talk about too much anymore. And Science Fiction is where people write who at least have

08:43.400 --> 08:49.880
a willingness to pay some lip service to a logical mind. Fantasy used to be a lot better

08:49.880 --> 08:56.060
when less people were writing it. But right now there's a lot of very mediocre writers writing,

08:56.240 --> 09:02.060
you know, good and evil fantasy or warmed over Christian mythology, which is not to me what

09:02.060 --> 09:08.200
fantasy is about. I love Conan, you know, original Howard stuff and all the real old stuff and Homer

09:08.200 --> 09:14.280
and Hesse had been, that to me is good fantasy. Science Fiction, when it's good, is great.

09:18.100 --> 09:24.500
The problem exists in Science Fiction in a different form where the young writers who don't

09:25.220 --> 09:32.300
really have a good conceptual basis in Science Fiction use what I call nuts and bolts, which is

09:32.300 --> 09:38.860
just data that they can get from encyclopedia as their science and have a little trick ending in

09:38.860 --> 09:44.940
which some scientific principle is involved to resolve the plot. But for me, good Science Fiction

09:44.940 --> 09:52.500
has the science as an integral part of the development of the story and you couldn't have the story

09:53.020 --> 10:01.900
without the scientific principle or the theoretical questions that you're basing it on. In other

10:01.900 --> 10:05.820
words, if you can take the science out of it and you still got a story, then you shouldn't have

10:05.820 --> 10:12.200
Science Fiction. It should be something else, TV, something like that. But Science Fiction should have

10:13.420 --> 10:17.600
almost the science and the theory or the world or whatever you want to call it, the structure that

10:17.600 --> 10:23.520
you're making it as a central character and that's what it does, when it does it best frees the mind

10:23.520 --> 10:27.880
and allows people to come away with lots of good questions that they can think about rather than

10:27.880 --> 10:32.320
providing tad answers which indeed you have a very limited lifespan we've all seen.

10:33.180 --> 10:35.180
Moore with Janet Morris on our next show.

