11:54.780 --> 12:00.020
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on Science Fiction and Fantasy.

12:02.900 --> 12:04.360
And here are your hosts.

12:08.560 --> 12:13.160
This is Bill Vernon and Daryl Lane. Science Fiction author Janet Morris' Saga of the

12:13.160 --> 12:17.820
Karrion Empire is a trilogy comprising dream dancer, cruiser dreams and earth dreams.

12:18.300 --> 12:22.520
The time is the 23rd century and the milieu is earth and several human colonized planets

12:22.520 --> 12:27.240
and far away star systems. The heroine is Sheba, a teenager from earth which by this time has

12:27.240 --> 12:31.880
reverted to a medieval culture. The trilogy describes her coming of age as a ward of the

12:31.880 --> 12:36.620
rulers of the human empire, the Karrion family. The saga of the Karrion Empire is an exciting

12:36.620 --> 12:41.540
blend of characterization, speculative physics and political intrigue. We asked Morris if she

12:41.540 --> 12:46.060
plotted the whole series in detail before she wrote it. I was going to do three, I signed

12:46.060 --> 12:50.900
form before I did them. Three was all there was going to be, three is all there is going to be.

12:51.400 --> 12:55.220
You know, unless something drastically changes then I see where it's someplace that I'd like to

12:55.220 --> 13:01.400
take it. I knew exactly what I wanted to talk about physics and the rest of it. I was,

13:01.400 --> 13:05.700
I wanted to create a female character that had all the flaws that Estre did not,

13:06.160 --> 13:12.680
that was totally opposite. And to talk a little about politics, I come from a very

13:14.360 --> 13:20.020
political background. My half sister was Carter speech writer on economic policy. I know way too

13:20.020 --> 13:26.200
much about politics to suit me. And I wanted to talk a little bit about politics and decision

13:26.200 --> 13:35.100
making at higher levels and what indeed happens to the people involved in it and the people

13:35.100 --> 13:40.820
affected by it who have no control of it. And the nice stuff for me that balanced it off was

13:44.020 --> 13:48.660
the culture that was comfortable with its technology growing into its technology,

13:48.660 --> 13:54.020
growing along with its technology. And I mean for me the cruisers were the main characters there.

13:54.020 --> 14:00.720
I loved doing the cruisers sections although they were very difficult at times to make it really

14:03.100 --> 14:08.840
seem as if they were cruises. And you know one never knows if one succeeded but for me they really

14:08.840 --> 14:15.820
were cruises. Plus I had the whole of history to draw on instead of having culture that had nothing

14:15.820 --> 14:20.160
to do with us. I had a culture that had everything to do with us. There had been no collapse, no

14:20.160 --> 14:25.700
world war three, everything had proceeded at pace and just gotten worse. The problems with

14:25.700 --> 14:29.720
quantum mechanics hadn't been solved, the problems with anything else had been solved and we were

14:29.720 --> 14:35.400
just sort of muddling along the way we tend to do. And that to me was a lot of fun. But as I said

14:35.400 --> 14:41.160
I did the partial and it went to auction in two countries on the partial and I was so

14:41.160 --> 14:47.760
slow to hear in England at the same time had two editors trying to keep the volumes consistent.

14:47.760 --> 14:52.680
Every editor has a different idea of what exactly they want you to do and they all want to mix them.

14:53.580 --> 14:57.780
It's very seldom you get an editor that leaves you totally alone. It doesn't bother you at all

14:57.780 --> 15:04.780
about a book. And I had to split the difference on one occasion between them and one editor wanted

15:04.780 --> 15:09.280
one section to be longer and the other one wanted the same section to be shorter in the same

15:09.980 --> 15:17.740
just the same 30 pages. And I ended up doing a prologue which seemed to satisfy them both. I

15:17.740 --> 15:23.600
had done that. So they work whole-bloodedly meant to be exactly what they are.

15:24.120 --> 15:27.960
Morris told us that she wrote this trilogy with the mature, literate, scientifically

15:27.960 --> 15:33.780
sophisticated reader in mind. Apparently her strategy worked. So I go to these conventions

15:33.780 --> 15:38.300
and they'd all raise their hands and say yes they want more science and yes they were ready to work

15:38.300 --> 15:43.940
a little and yes they wanted to be challenged and I said okay, well we don't. And I wrote a book in

15:43.940 --> 15:52.440
which I wrote to my ideal reader, didn't talk down, didn't simplify it, did what I consider a good

15:52.440 --> 15:59.180
job of explaining mathematics as poetry and just let fly. And so far the reaction to it's been very

15:59.180 --> 16:03.060
good as I told you the first printing has had been through two printings before publication

16:03.060 --> 16:08.920
or in three. It has been doing very well. You get some people that don't want to work but I think

16:08.920 --> 16:14.580
there's enough story there to carry them over the parts that they are not willing to try to understand.

16:15.420 --> 16:17.260
More with Janet Morris on our next show.

